<task id="AIPU2-020" project="Spaarke AI Platform Unification R2">
  <metadata>
    <title>Build PromptShieldService — Azure AI Content Safety Integration</title>
    <phase>2B</phase>
    <tags>bff-api, ai-safety, content-safety</tags>
    <status>not-started</status>
    <estimated-effort>4 hours</estimated-effort>
    <dependencies>AIPU2-003, AIPU2-006</dependencies>
    <parallel-safe>false</parallel-safe>
  </metadata>
  <prompt>
    Build PromptShieldService, which calls the Azure AI Content Safety Prompt Shields API to detect prompt
    injection attempts in both user messages and documents retrieved from the knowledge base. This is the
    primary defense-in-depth layer against adversarial inputs embedded in uploaded documents or chat turns.
    When an injection is detected, the request is blocked before reaching the LLM and the user receives a
    clear but non-alarming message. The service must complete in under 100ms to stay within the streaming
    first-token latency budget.
  </prompt>
  <role>Senior .NET security engineer with Azure AI Content Safety API experience.</role>
  <goal>
    Prompt injection attempts in user messages and retrieved documents are detected and blocked before reaching
    the orchestrator LLM. Detection latency is under 100ms. SAFE inputs pass through with no user-visible impact.
  </goal>
  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>.claude/constraints/ai.md</file>
      <file>docs/architecture/AI-ARCHITECTURE.md</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/</file>
      <file>docs/architecture/auth-AI-azure-resources.md</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>
  <steps>
    <step>Read AI-ARCHITECTURE.md and auth-AI-azure-resources.md to find the Content Safety endpoint, API key secret name, and any existing HTTP client registrations.</step>
    <step>Create IPromptShieldService.cs interface with: Task&lt;PromptShieldResult&gt; ScanAsync(PromptShieldRequest request, CancellationToken ct).</step>
    <step>Create PromptShieldRequest.cs record: UserMessage (string), Documents (IReadOnlyList&lt;string&gt; — retrieved passage texts, can be empty).</step>
    <step>Create PromptShieldResult.cs record: IsBlocked (bool), BlockReason (enum: None, UserInjection, DocumentInjection), DetectedAttackType (string?), LatencyMs (double).</step>
    <step>Create PromptShieldService.cs implementing IPromptShieldService. Use IHttpClientFactory to get a named client "ContentSafety". Call POST https://{endpoint}/contentsafety/text:shieldPrompt?api-version=2024-09-01 with body { "userPrompt": message, "documents": [...] }.</step>
    <step>Parse the API response: check attackDetected in userPromptAnalysis and documentsAnalysis. Map to PromptShieldResult. If either is true, set IsBlocked = true and set BlockReason appropriately.</step>
    <step>Handle failure modes: HTTP 429 → log and set IsBlocked = false (fail-open with warning), HTTP 5xx → same fail-open behavior, timeout (&gt;100ms) → fail-open with warning. Always log the failure reason.</step>
    <step>Register named HttpClient "ContentSafety" with BaseAddress from IConfiguration["AiSafety:ContentSafety:Endpoint"] and Ocp-Apim-Subscription-Key header from Key Vault. Register IPromptShieldService in AddAiSafetyModule() extension method.</step>
    <step>Integrate into the AI request pipeline: call PromptShieldService.ScanAsync before the LLM call. If IsBlocked, return a streaming SSE error event with user-friendly message "I was unable to process that request." and end the stream.</step>
    <step>Emit OTEL counter ai_safety_prompt_shield_blocked_total (label reason=user_injection|document_injection) and histogram ai_safety_prompt_shield_latency_ms.</step>
    <step>Write unit tests with mocked HttpClient: user injection detected → blocked, document injection detected → blocked, SAFE → not blocked, HTTP 429 → fail-open, timeout → fail-open.</step>
    <step>Run `dotnet build` and `dotnet test --filter "PromptShield"` to verify.</step>
  </steps>
  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion>User messages containing known injection patterns are blocked before reaching the LLM.</criterion>
    <criterion>Retrieved documents containing injection patterns are blocked before reaching the LLM.</criterion>
    <criterion>SAFE inputs pass through with no user-visible impact and no stream interruption.</criterion>
    <criterion>Blocked requests return a user-friendly SSE error message and terminate the stream.</criterion>
    <criterion>Service completes in under 100ms (P95) — verified by histogram in tests.</criterion>
    <criterion>HTTP 429 and timeouts result in fail-open behavior (not blocked), with warning logged.</criterion>
    <criterion>OTEL counter and histogram emitted correctly.</criterion>
    <criterion>Unit tests pass: `dotnet test --filter "PromptShield"`.</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>
</task>
